Let me reconsider the problem. Maybe I'm missing something very basic. Let me look at what the `unix_peek_fds` function does one more time:

```c
static void unix_peek_fds(struct scm_cookie *scm, struct sk_buff *skb)
{
    scm->fp = scm_fp_dup(UNIXCB(skb).fp);
    spin_lock(&unix_gc_lock);
    spin_unlock(&unix_gc_lock);
}
```

The function assigns `scm->fp = scm_fp_dup(UNIXCB(skb).fp)`. The `scm` is a parameter. Looking at the callers:

In `__unix_dgram_recvmsg`:
```c
memset(&scm, 0, sizeof(scm));
...
if (UNIXCB(skb).fp)
    unix_peek_fds(&scm, skb);
...
scm_recv_unix(sock, msg, &scm, flags);
```

After `unix_peek_fds`, `scm.fp` is set. Then `scm_recv_unix` is called which processes the fp.

In `unix_stream_read_generic`:
```c
memset(&scm, 0, sizeof(scm));
...
do {
    ...
    if (UNIXCB(skb).fp)
        unix_peek_fds(&scm, skb);
    ...
} while (size);

mutex_unlock(&u->iolock);
if (state->msg)
    scm_recv_unix(sock, state->msg, &scm, flags);
else
    scm_destroy(&scm);
```

Same pattern. `scm` is zero-initialized, `unix_peek_fds` sets `scm.fp`, then `scm_recv_unix` or `scm_destroy` processes it.

This all seems correct. The only potential issue I can see is if `scm_fp_dup` returns NULL (allocation failure), but that's handled because `scm_recv_unix` checks `if (scm->fp)` before calling `scm_detach_fds`.

